33:44.820 --> 33:47.820
And if you follow them out, you can see that it's a large

33:47.820 --> 33:51.660
Australopithesis probably, Australopithecus walking with

33:51.660 --> 33:53.780
a small one, and they walk, and they turn and look at

33:53.780 --> 33:55.980
something, and then they walk on.

33:55.980 --> 33:59.620
And it rained after they had walked by, and this is volcanic

33:59.620 --> 34:01.820
ash that hardened like concrete and left their

34:01.820 --> 34:03.620
footprints there.

34:03.620 --> 34:06.460
This is Australopithecus africanus.

34:06.460 --> 34:09.420
And as far as we can tell, they're the first creature to

34:09.420 --> 34:11.620
ever preserve an icon.

34:11.620 --> 34:16.980
So they're starting to look at things and contemplate, I

34:16.980 --> 34:18.460
don't think that's too strong a word,

34:18.460 --> 34:19.740
contemplate the similarities.

34:19.740 --> 34:23.740
So this stone, which is about 3 million years old, is called

34:23.740 --> 34:25.140
the Makapansgat pebble.

34:25.140 --> 34:28.860
It was found in a cave in South Africa, and it's unlike

34:28.860 --> 34:33.780
the material that the other stones in the cave were from.

34:33.780 --> 34:39.180
And if you look at it, it has an interesting characteristic.

34:39.180 --> 34:41.900
It looks like a smiley face.

34:41.900 --> 34:45.740
And this thing is about 3 inches by 2 inches, so it's too

34:45.740 --> 34:48.780
big to have gotten caught between their toes and carried

34:48.780 --> 34:50.900
up there coincidentally.

34:50.900 --> 34:53.540
This seems to be something that Australopithecus and

34:53.540 --> 34:56.420
Australopithecus found interesting and carried up to

34:56.420 --> 35:01.140
the cave with no particular functional role other than it

35:01.140 --> 35:04.100
looked like a face.

35:04.100 --> 35:07.300
Australopithecines also made tools.

35:07.340 --> 35:11.540
They're tools about 3.3 million years old, found in

35:11.540 --> 35:12.300
different places.

35:12.300 --> 35:17.340
They're the Oldowan tools discovered initially by the

35:17.340 --> 35:20.220
Leakey family.

35:20.220 --> 35:22.740
Icons are all over the place.

35:22.740 --> 35:26.180
In addition to seeing icons in nature, we have them in

35:26.180 --> 35:28.420
churches, and here are tools that have been actually made

35:28.420 --> 35:33.300
into icons and symbols, both.

35:33.300 --> 35:36.420
And from symbols to grammar, so how complex does a

35:36.420 --> 35:37.300
grammar have to be?

35:37.300 --> 35:40.340
Everybody will agree, every linguist will agree that you

35:40.340 --> 35:44.900
can't have a language until you have a grammar.

35:44.900 --> 35:47.220
But how complex does the grammar have to be?

35:47.220 --> 35:49.700
Well, there are a couple of different possibilities.

35:49.700 --> 35:53.500
And one of the points that I make in the book is that we

35:53.500 --> 35:55.860
find all of these in the world today.

35:55.860 --> 36:00.060
So one we could call a G1 grammar, which is just words

36:00.060 --> 36:02.220
put in a linear order.

36:02.260 --> 36:06.940
And that seems to be the case, for example, in Peta Ha and

36:06.940 --> 36:11.100
Riau, which is a language of New Guinea, which is

36:11.100 --> 36:13.060
John Saul Mary.

36:13.060 --> 36:15.100
So there's no other structure, let's say, in a

36:15.100 --> 36:15.820
language like this.

36:15.820 --> 36:20.140
There's just those three words, John Saul Mary.

36:20.140 --> 36:25.500
A G2 grammar would be like a G1 grammar, but have additional

36:25.500 --> 36:27.620
hierarchy or structure into the phrases.

36:27.620 --> 36:34.140
So the man you saw yesterday is here, where you saw

36:34.140 --> 36:40.180
yesterday as a sentence hierarchically located inside

36:40.180 --> 36:44.940
a larger sentence, or you could simply say the very big

36:44.940 --> 36:47.220
ball rolled down the hill.

36:47.220 --> 36:48.860
There you start to get more structure.

36:48.860 --> 36:51.660
It's not simply linear order of words.

36:51.660 --> 36:54.980
A G3 grammar has both recursion and hierarchy.

36:54.980 --> 36:56.300
So what is recursion?

36:56.300 --> 36:59.260
It's the ability to put one thing inside another of the

36:59.260 --> 37:01.020
same type and just keep doing it.

37:01.020 --> 37:08.340
So the man who is here said that Bill said that Mary said

37:08.340 --> 37:12.180
that Peter said that John bought a house.

37:12.180 --> 37:14.180
When you start to get structures like that so that

37:14.180 --> 37:17.340
you can say there's no longer a sentence in a language, then

37:17.340 --> 37:19.140
recursion is the best way to handle that.

37:19.140 --> 37:22.180
And recursion is communicatively very useful.

37:22.180 --> 37:24.260
You can pack a lot more information in a

37:24.260 --> 37:27.340
sentence with recursion.

37:27.340 --> 37:30.740
But I've argued that although recursion can be found in any

37:30.740 --> 37:33.980
language, it's not a necessary component of all languages.

37:33.980 --> 37:36.140
And in fact, there are good reasons why some

37:36.140 --> 37:37.500
languages would avoid it.

37:39.940 --> 37:41.820
So erectus had icons.

37:41.820 --> 37:43.500
We know that they carry things around.

37:43.500 --> 37:46.940
They didn't carry around smiley faces that we know of, but

37:46.940 --> 37:51.300
they did carry around phallic symbols like this cuttlefish

37:51.300 --> 37:57.620
bone that was found in Morocco about 450,000 years ago.

37:57.620 --> 38:02.980
And erectus also started making quite complex tools.

38:02.980 --> 38:07.460
So there are three grades of tools in the paleolithic,

38:07.460 --> 38:09.460
especially in the lower paleolithic.

38:09.460 --> 38:11.940
There are oldivon tools about 3 million years ago.

38:11.940 --> 38:16.020
There are achulian tools made as recently as 200,000 years

38:16.020 --> 38:16.820
ago.

38:16.820 --> 38:19.980
And then finally, there are levelwa tools, which are the

38:19.980 --> 38:24.060
most complex tools found in the paleolithic.

38:24.060 --> 38:27.180
So these are refined, which means they've been thinned.

38:27.180 --> 38:32.140
These take quite a bit of effort and skill to function.

38:32.140 --> 38:34.700
And they have various parts to them.

38:34.700 --> 38:37.580
You don't just start off banging two rocks together to

38:37.580 --> 38:38.260
get one of those.

38:38.260 --> 38:39.780
You have to have a plan.

38:39.780 --> 38:42.620
There are certain things that have to be cut out of the tool.

38:42.620 --> 38:47.100
It has to have a certain shape to be functional.

38:47.100 --> 38:49.220
So when erectus started working on tools, they might

38:49.260 --> 38:50.700
start with a large piece of rock.

38:50.700 --> 38:53.900
And out of that, they had to break out the pieces that

38:53.900 --> 38:57.220
they needed to get the kind of functional tool.

38:57.220 --> 39:02.780
And they make them all pretty much the same to work for them.

39:02.780 --> 39:05.140
Erectus was the first to come up with a controlled use of

39:05.140 --> 39:06.140
fire.

39:06.140 --> 39:09.540
The pre-shaping of stone tools, working them before they

39:09.540 --> 39:12.980
actually started chiseling out the tools, they used wood and

39:12.980 --> 39:14.580
bone tools as well.

39:14.580 --> 39:17.180
And we think they might have also used hafted tools.

39:17.180 --> 39:19.820
And hafted tools are quite important because that's when

39:19.820 --> 39:23.140
you tie a handle on that shows a lot of functional

39:23.140 --> 39:24.500
improvement over others.

39:24.500 --> 39:28.020
And it shows a lot of foresight and planning.

39:28.020 --> 39:35.620
So these tools had a great deal of complexity over

39:35.620 --> 39:37.420
hundreds of thousands of years.

39:37.420 --> 39:43.340
And in recent research in modern-day Ghana, Larry

39:43.340 --> 39:47.500
Barham has discovered about 900,000-year-old tools that

39:47.500 --> 39:50.820
seem to have been dyed with ochre.

39:50.820 --> 39:54.340
That's a significant finding because dyeing tools shows

39:54.340 --> 39:59.380
that that's not simply a functional aspect of toolmaking.

39:59.380 --> 40:04.340
That is an aspect of toolmaking that shows thought

40:04.340 --> 40:07.140
that goes above the mere function of the tool.

40:07.140 --> 40:10.780
Hafting tools, combinatorial thinking, imagining the

40:10.780 --> 40:14.660
future, and likely invented by erectus.

40:14.660 --> 40:16.620
It's one of the most significant technological

40:16.620 --> 40:20.220
breakthroughs in human toolmaking.

40:20.220 --> 40:23.340
And ochre is also very important.

40:23.340 --> 40:26.420
And we see things like hand axes.

40:26.420 --> 40:29.980
They had a tool kit, not nearly as extensive as an

40:29.980 --> 40:33.260
Neanderthal tool kit or as a Homo sapiens tool kit, but as

40:33.260 --> 40:35.820
an extensive tool kit.

40:35.820 --> 40:37.700
They had hand axes and cleavers.

40:37.700 --> 40:39.540
They had picks.

40:39.580 --> 40:41.180
And so we see different stages.

40:41.180 --> 40:43.980
We should recall the simple stage of Oldowan tools that we

40:43.980 --> 40:47.860
saw that Australopithecus had.

40:47.860 --> 40:49.500
We see achulian tools.

40:49.500 --> 40:52.060
These are already starting to get refined and showing a lot

40:52.060 --> 40:53.340
more work.

40:53.340 --> 40:57.860
And then we get to the Cadillac of the tools of

40:57.860 --> 41:01.420
erectus-level-wa tools.

41:01.420 --> 41:04.220
Not everyone agrees that erectus-made-level-wa tools.

41:04.900 --> 41:11.900
Some are dated as early as 625,000 BC.

41:11.900 --> 41:13.900
But not everyone agrees with those dates.

41:13.900 --> 41:18.980
The dates that do have the widest agreement are about

41:18.980 --> 41:22.740
300,000 years ago.

41:22.740 --> 41:24.900
That would mean that they could have been used by

41:24.900 --> 41:27.420
Neanderthals or sapiens or erectus.

41:27.420 --> 41:30.740
So it's difficult to limit them exclusively to erectus.

41:30.740 --> 41:33.820
However, a million years ago, we see larger tools that are

41:33.860 --> 41:37.300
made with the same way that level-wa tools are made.

41:37.300 --> 41:43.220
Level-wa tools require a lot of hammer work before the

41:43.220 --> 41:46.900
final stage, which is lifting the core out of the larger

41:46.900 --> 41:47.780
tool.

41:47.780 --> 41:51.700
And that takes a lot of planning, a lot of discussion,

41:51.700 --> 41:54.020
or a lot of skill.

41:54.020 --> 41:58.860
And many of the people who study the tools, a fairly wide

41:58.860 --> 42:02.980
consensus, is that level-wa tools can't be learned by

42:02.980 --> 42:04.020
imitation alone.

42:04.020 --> 42:07.620
There has to be linguistic instruction when we get to

42:07.620 --> 42:09.740
this level of tool complexity.

42:09.740 --> 42:14.620
And these tools were, in fact, found as early as a million

42:14.620 --> 42:18.380
years ago tools that were made by the same process.

42:18.380 --> 42:20.820
Not everyone would call them by the same name, but they

42:20.820 --> 42:22.940
were made by the same process.

42:22.940 --> 42:25.460
So every tool that was made had to have various

42:25.460 --> 42:26.540
functional features.

42:26.540 --> 42:31.020
So if we find tools that have nothing but functional

42:31.020 --> 42:35.220
features, it's difficult to see anything symbolic in that.

42:35.220 --> 42:38.820
We can say of any tool that it's an index of the task to

42:38.820 --> 42:42.100
be performed, it's an icon of other tools.

42:42.100 --> 42:44.580
You have one tool as a model to make another tool.

42:44.580 --> 42:51.300
So it does represent a growth in signification.

42:51.300 --> 42:53.420
But to get to the level of symbols, we need to see

42:53.420 --> 42:56.500
things that aren't simply part of the function.

42:56.500 --> 43:00.020
And we start to see some of this at the end of the

43:00.020 --> 43:00.980
Acheulean age.

43:00.980 --> 43:06.020
We see tools that are made a little bit more elaborately

43:06.020 --> 43:07.140
than they need to be made.

43:07.140 --> 43:10.940
They're painted, they're dyed.

43:10.940 --> 43:13.940
And in fact, when Larry and I were working on some tools

43:13.940 --> 43:19.180
that he had just brought back from Africa this past summer,

43:19.180 --> 43:23.500
another expert on erectus tools walked into his lab at

43:23.500 --> 43:27.020
Liverpool and said, oh, those are from East Africa.

43:27.020 --> 43:32.620
Because apparently East African and West African erectus

43:32.620 --> 43:35.540
designed their tools in different ways.

43:35.540 --> 43:38.540
So the design of the tools was representative of the group

43:38.540 --> 43:39.900
that they came from.

43:39.900 --> 43:43.940
They indicated robustness.

43:43.940 --> 43:46.540
One of the earliest ideas when they started to find these

43:46.540 --> 43:50.300
non-functional aspects of erectus tools was that it was

43:50.300 --> 43:53.660
men showing off for women, making the tools to show that

43:53.660 --> 43:54.740
they were better tool makers.

43:54.740 --> 43:56.580
But of course, we have no idea whether it was men who made

43:56.580 --> 43:58.660
the tools or women who made the tools.

43:58.660 --> 43:59.500
So we don't know.

43:59.500 --> 44:01.380
There was somebody who was probably showing off, but we

44:01.380 --> 44:02.940
don't know who was showing off.

44:02.940 --> 44:06.860
But then we find really interesting things about

44:06.860 --> 44:11.460
erectus that are difficult to explain.

44:11.460 --> 44:16.620
And we find that, so this shell is 750,000 years old.

44:16.620 --> 44:20.140
And the markings on this shell were done in Java by a

44:20.140 --> 44:25.380
homo erectus using a shark tooth on this large shell.

44:25.380 --> 44:28.020
And the marks were made without ever picking up the shark

44:28.020 --> 44:32.340
tooth, their constant continuous representation.

44:32.340 --> 44:34.740
And we start to see a lot of this kind of thing with

44:34.740 --> 44:39.100
erectus, this kind of attempt to represent things such as

44:39.100 --> 44:39.980
this rock.

44:39.980 --> 44:43.580
We find these geometric shapes that erectus is starting to

44:43.580 --> 44:47.340
carve into shells and into tools so that we realize that

44:47.340 --> 44:50.900
erectus is starting to see things beyond their mere

44:50.900 --> 44:52.260
functionality.

44:52.300 --> 44:57.860
And then about 250,000 years ago, we find this Venus of

44:57.860 --> 45:01.980
Barakat Ram, which is in the Israel Museum in Jerusalem,

45:01.980 --> 45:08.500
which has got red ochre on it, partially formed by humans,

45:08.500 --> 45:10.940
partially formed by nature.

45:10.940 --> 45:14.460
But it's the first real artwork that we know about.

45:14.460 --> 45:16.300
There are others about the same time.

45:16.300 --> 45:19.460
And it does seem to have been made by erectus.

45:19.460 --> 45:24.220
So erectus tools, they have symbolic and social components.

45:24.220 --> 45:26.220
They go beyond the functionally necessary.

45:26.220 --> 45:27.220
They go into style.

45:27.220 --> 45:29.460
They represent one tradition over another.

45:29.460 --> 45:32.300
They're beyond icons and indexes.

45:32.300 --> 45:35.740
They're simultaneously indexes of task, icons of other

45:35.740 --> 45:37.980
tools, and symbols of the values and labor of the

45:37.980 --> 45:40.540
community.

45:40.540 --> 45:44.300
Symbols in linear order simply turn out to be language.

45:44.300 --> 45:47.780
As soon as you can start symbolizing things, you have

45:47.780 --> 45:50.660
the ingredients that are necessary for language.

45:50.660 --> 45:55.220
So if they had language, what other things did they do that

45:55.220 --> 45:57.140
might have shown that they had language?

45:57.140 --> 46:01.540
So the tools show us that they had the ability to symbolize

46:01.540 --> 46:04.180
and this would have been a cognitive

46:04.180 --> 46:05.900
breakthrough for language.

46:05.900 --> 46:08.180
But is there any other evidence?

46:08.180 --> 46:09.780
Well, it turns out that there are.

46:09.780 --> 46:12.180
But let's talk about how you get to modern languages from

46:12.180 --> 46:13.380
just a few symbols.

46:13.380 --> 46:16.060
Most things are enhancements.

46:16.100 --> 46:17.300
So we add things.

46:17.300 --> 46:20.740
So you have language systems that decide what they're

46:20.740 --> 46:21.540
going to represent.

46:21.540 --> 46:23.020
What is it that you want to talk about?

46:23.020 --> 46:26.460
So among the pita ha, for example, there are no numbers.

46:26.460 --> 46:27.460
There are no color words.

46:27.460 --> 46:28.900
They don't have the number one.

46:28.900 --> 46:31.980
Does this mean that they're cognitively deficient?

46:31.980 --> 46:34.620
Well, they also don't have golf clubs.

46:34.620 --> 46:36.340
There are a lot of things they don't have and a lot of

46:36.340 --> 46:37.220
things we don't have.

46:37.220 --> 46:41.900
How many men in here know how to make a good bow and arrow?

46:41.900 --> 46:44.020
They produce what their culture needs.

46:44.020 --> 46:45.740
Their culture doesn't need numbers.

46:45.740 --> 46:47.740
They don't have numbers.

46:47.740 --> 46:50.180
And this has been verified with a lot of experiments over

46:50.180 --> 46:52.060
the years.

46:52.060 --> 46:56.220
So they also don't represent tense, but they don't have

46:56.220 --> 46:58.380
past tense or present tense or future tense.

46:58.380 --> 47:02.220
But they have a lot of ways of distinguishing different

47:02.220 --> 47:05.260
perspectives on how an action takes place, whether it took

47:05.260 --> 47:07.620
place at a certain height, whether it took place near

47:07.620 --> 47:08.740
the river.

47:08.740 --> 47:10.660
So they build into their verbs.

47:10.660 --> 47:14.380
How many verb forms does English have?

47:14.380 --> 47:15.940
It's pretty poor.

47:15.940 --> 47:18.180
Five, sing, sing, sung, singing, sings.

47:18.180 --> 47:18.660
That's it.

47:18.660 --> 47:22.820
You've exhausted the entire word grammar of English with

47:22.820 --> 47:23.660
those.

47:23.660 --> 47:26.980
But if you go on to Spanish or Portuguese, you'll get 30 to

47:26.980 --> 47:29.060
50 types of verbs.

47:29.060 --> 47:34.100
But in Pida ha, since there are 16 suffixes possible, you

47:34.100 --> 47:37.900
have two to the 16 possible verb forms, which is about

47:37.900 --> 47:40.260
65,000 verb forms.

47:40.260 --> 47:43.060
So their grammar is not like ours.

47:43.060 --> 47:47.140
It has very complex verbs, but simple in other ways

47:47.140 --> 47:49.740
compared to us.

47:49.740 --> 47:52.620
It's what a culture decides to represent that starts to work

47:52.620 --> 47:55.100
its way into the language.

47:55.100 --> 47:58.580
Conceptual systems, how do we interpret these things?

47:58.580 --> 48:00.940
Do we interpret these things strictly based on the symbols

48:00.940 --> 48:01.420
we see?

48:01.420 --> 48:05.900
Do we interpret them based on other cultural nuances?

48:05.900 --> 48:08.260
And these all start to form part of the language and enter

48:08.260 --> 48:09.780
the language in different ways.

48:09.820 --> 48:13.420
Linguistic systems will have different rules, different

48:13.420 --> 48:16.300
structures, different constraints.

48:16.300 --> 48:21.140
So this shows that language has at least these major

48:21.140 --> 48:24.300
components, the objects, the ways they're interpreted, and

48:24.300 --> 48:26.340
the forms that we choose to represent them in.

48:26.340 --> 48:27.500
And languages differ a lot.

48:27.500 --> 48:30.500
So if I say yesterday, what did John give to Mary in the

48:30.500 --> 48:33.380
library, there's intonation.

48:33.380 --> 48:38.940
My pitch is modulated, depending on whether it's a

48:38.940 --> 48:41.220
question or a statement.

48:41.220 --> 48:43.500
And these are add-ons to make things clear.

48:43.500 --> 48:46.740
It's not necessary to have this intuition to distinguish

48:46.740 --> 48:50.700
questions from statements, but it is very, very useful.

48:50.700 --> 48:53.780
In Piedah, like many of the world's languages, probably

48:53.780 --> 48:56.780
close to half of the world's languages, such as Chinese and

48:56.780 --> 48:58.780
Korean and others, the language is tonal.

48:58.780 --> 49:02.460
So the word for ear in Piedah is awe.

49:02.460 --> 49:05.180
And the word for foreigner is awe.

49:05.180 --> 49:07.180
And the word for skin is awe.

49:07.180 --> 49:09.860
And the word for Brazilian shell is awe.

49:09.860 --> 49:13.460
And the word for hand is awe.

49:13.460 --> 49:21.300
So if I whistled it, and those are all very important in

49:21.300 --> 49:21.660
Piedah.

49:21.660 --> 49:24.540
So you've got to be able to hear those tonal distinctions.

49:24.540 --> 49:27.620
But obviously, tone's not necessary, because we don't

49:27.620 --> 49:28.380
have it in English.

49:28.380 --> 49:31.700
And although English may not be as attractive sounding as

49:31.700 --> 49:34.860
Piedah, it still seems to work.

49:34.860 --> 49:36.900
So there are all sorts of things we can add.

49:36.900 --> 49:39.300
Once we get symbols, there are all ways that we can embellish

49:39.300 --> 49:42.500
them with sound structures and the kinds of syllables we use,

49:42.500 --> 49:45.980
the way we organize things.

49:45.980 --> 49:48.740
And then we start to think about how languages

49:48.740 --> 49:50.380
represented in the brain.

49:50.380 --> 49:54.220
And in the work of Evelina Fedorenko at MIT's Brain and

49:54.220 --> 49:59.460
Cognitive Sciences Department, she's found that languages,

49:59.460 --> 50:02.420
not at all, found in just one part of the brain, as people

50:02.420 --> 50:04.860
thought for many years, but that it's distributed

50:04.860 --> 50:09.140
throughout the brain in what she calls a language network.

50:09.140 --> 50:14.220
And that this network is fairly similar across all languages

50:14.220 --> 50:16.660
and across all people.

50:16.660 --> 50:19.140
But it's a lot more complicated than simply saying it's in

50:19.140 --> 50:21.900
Broca's area, if you've heard of that area, or

50:21.900 --> 50:23.180
Vernike's area.

50:23.180 --> 50:25.700
Actually, the interesting thing about Broca's patient is

50:25.700 --> 50:29.300
the part of his brain that was damaged was not Broca's area.

50:29.300 --> 50:35.820
But simplistic views of where language is found in the brain

50:35.820 --> 50:39.500
are being challenged every day by more research.

50:39.500 --> 50:45.620
So there are various ways that we enhance grammar in morphemes,

50:45.620 --> 50:49.820
our little parts of words, like the 65,000 Piedoha word forms.

50:49.820 --> 50:52.500
There are phrases, sentences, paragraphs, discourses,

50:52.500 --> 50:53.340
conversations.

50:53.340 --> 50:57.780
All of these are important, and they occur naturally over time.

50:57.780 --> 51:01.380
The interesting thing about language, although it's very

51:01.380 --> 51:04.780
complicated, once we start to look at a finished system, we

51:04.780 --> 51:07.660
can see that its components are relatively simple and build up

51:07.660 --> 51:11.580
over time, and that the core component to every aspect of

51:11.580 --> 51:14.780
the language that's been built up is the symbol.

51:14.780 --> 51:17.220
So what else did erectus do?

51:17.220 --> 51:21.500
Well, just under two million years ago, they were spread

51:21.500 --> 51:23.020
out across the world.

51:23.020 --> 51:26.260
That we find them in Beijing, we find them in Iran, we find

51:26.260 --> 51:29.260
them in various parts of the world.

51:29.260 --> 51:30.180
We find erectus.

51:30.180 --> 51:34.780
There were still many in Africa, and so they were traveling.

51:34.780 --> 51:40.980
And we find a 790,000-year-old settlement in Israel,

51:40.980 --> 51:43.620
Geshe Benoit Yaakov.

51:43.620 --> 51:45.860
And in there, we find the controlled use of fire,

51:45.860 --> 51:52.420
specialized spaces, various components that show, for

51:52.420 --> 51:56.860
example, separate areas of the settlement are used for

51:56.860 --> 52:00.300
processing meat, processing fish, processing plant, what

52:00.300 --> 52:02.140
seem to be communal areas.

52:02.140 --> 52:07.660
So erectus did seem to have the ability to have an

52:07.660 --> 52:08.540
organized society.

52:08.540 --> 52:13.500
There's evidence that their society was organized.

52:13.500 --> 52:16.820
And this is found in this ongoing work in Israel and

52:16.820 --> 52:17.580
other places.

52:17.580 --> 52:21.100
This is found where the black dot is, is an erectus

52:21.100 --> 52:22.380
settlement in Israel.

52:22.380 --> 52:26.020
There are a lot of interesting archaic human sites in the

52:26.020 --> 52:28.860
Middle East, in Israel, and other places.

52:28.860 --> 52:31.220
Because if you're coming out of Africa at the time they were

52:31.220 --> 52:34.900
coming out, because the Sahara Desert was actually a lush

52:34.900 --> 52:37.980
green forest, you come out, turn right.

52:37.980 --> 52:39.460
And it's all you can do.

52:39.460 --> 52:40.860
You can't go straight, because that's the ocean.

52:40.860 --> 52:43.780
Turn right, and you're in the Middle East.

52:43.780 --> 52:45.780
And that's why we find those to be some of the

52:45.780 --> 52:46.340
earliest settlements.

52:46.340 --> 52:50.300
So here's the excavation in Israel, finding these

52:50.300 --> 52:52.740
different aspects of it.

52:52.740 --> 52:59.180
There's also good evidence that erectus traveled across

52:59.180 --> 53:03.660
distances they could not see across in the ocean.

53:03.660 --> 53:05.300
And there are several interesting

53:05.300 --> 53:06.500
things to draw from this.

53:06.500 --> 53:09.860
First of all, most marine archaeologists argue that you

53:09.860 --> 53:13.940
can't have a viable human community without 20 to 40

53:13.940 --> 53:18.140
people arriving roughly at the same time in an area.

53:18.140 --> 53:21.900
So when we find evidence of viable human culture in

53:21.900 --> 53:26.740
places like Flores in Indonesia, so if you look at

53:26.740 --> 53:30.700
the island of Flores in Indonesia, the point where

53:30.700 --> 53:34.540
erectus would have had to cross is about 28 miles.

53:34.540 --> 53:38.100
So it's about the size of the English Channel.

53:38.100 --> 53:40.940
You could think, well, people swim the English Channel, and

53:40.940 --> 53:43.700
we know that other animals could swim across.

53:43.700 --> 53:49.340
But Flores is split off from the rest of what would have

53:49.340 --> 53:53.620
been at that time the mainland by the strongest ocean

53:53.620 --> 53:54.620
current in the world.

53:54.620 --> 53:57.300
It's called the Pacific Through Flow.

53:57.300 --> 54:01.900
And it was the same current back then, 750,000 years ago,

54:01.900 --> 54:02.620
as far as we can tell.

54:02.620 --> 54:05.500
So it was too difficult for a human to swim

54:05.500 --> 54:06.380
across that current.

54:06.380 --> 54:09.340
In fact, if you just put a raft in the water or just put a

54:09.340 --> 54:13.100
log in the water and start off, you're going to get

54:13.100 --> 54:14.420
washed out to sea.

54:14.420 --> 54:15.700
You're not going to make it to Flores.

54:15.700 --> 54:17.100
The current is too strong.

54:17.100 --> 54:20.700
So for humans who have gotten there, it's highly likely

54:20.700 --> 54:23.940
that they had boat-building capability.

54:23.940 --> 54:28.180
In fact, an archaeologist in Australia, Robert Bednarik,

54:28.180 --> 54:34.940
has built boats using erectus tools, etchulian tools, and

54:34.940 --> 54:38.700
level-wa tools, and shown that he can build boats that

54:38.700 --> 54:41.380
can get there in that period of time.

54:41.380 --> 54:44.700
The question is, could they have done that without language?

54:44.700 --> 54:49.940
And there's an article by a moxplunk evolutionary

54:49.940 --> 54:53.500
anthropologist, David Gill, called, how much grammar do

54:53.500 --> 54:55.300
you need to build a boat?

54:55.300 --> 54:59.300
And he argues that you actually don't need much grammar,

54:59.300 --> 55:01.780
but you do need language to be able to build a boat.

55:01.780 --> 55:04.340
And so the idea that they could sail, and this is a

55:04.340 --> 55:07.860
controversial idea, most things said about the past are

55:07.860 --> 55:11.980
controversial, because you can say they got there, and they

55:11.980 --> 55:14.220
had to get there in a certain number.

55:14.220 --> 55:16.460
But you can't show that they got several places.

55:16.460 --> 55:21.020
The ideal thing would be to show them in places where we

55:21.020 --> 55:21.500
know.

55:21.500 --> 55:22.780
So some people have argued they got

55:22.780 --> 55:25.700
across by tsunamis, right?

55:25.700 --> 55:30.220
But that sort of defies the physics of tsunamis, which tend

55:30.220 --> 55:32.100
to come towards the land.

55:32.100 --> 55:34.740
Now there are cases of people who've been found out to see

55:34.740 --> 55:37.660
there was a Japanese guy found floating on a roof, I think,

55:37.660 --> 55:41.140
after the tsunami that hit Japan a couple of years ago.

55:41.140 --> 55:43.900
So it does occasionally happen, but it doesn't seem to be a

55:43.900 --> 55:48.380
very productive way of travel, sort of fortuitous.

55:48.380 --> 55:51.180
And they did this a lot, even in places where we don't know

55:51.180 --> 55:52.780
of tsunamis having hit.

55:52.780 --> 55:55.260
So Kotra, the Russian archaeological team, found

55:55.260 --> 56:01.580
evidence in Sokotra 1.4 million years ago, which is 150

56:01.580 --> 56:04.420
miles from the closest land.

56:04.420 --> 56:07.500
We start to see evidence of potential burial.

56:07.540 --> 56:10.220
This stone on the right is called Excalibur.

56:10.220 --> 56:14.700
It's a colored handaxe of the period, a Julian handaxe, and

56:14.700 --> 56:15.940
it was found in a grave.

56:15.940 --> 56:18.180
Does that mean it was buried on purpose with them?

56:18.180 --> 56:19.740
We start to see evidence of that.

56:19.740 --> 56:23.420
It's difficult to say convincingly that it was, but it

56:23.420 --> 56:27.100
is interesting that it was a colored handaxe found.

56:27.100 --> 56:29.620
Around the time that Neanderthal was starting to

56:29.620 --> 56:33.860
appear, the erectus Neanderthal transition period, we

56:33.860 --> 56:38.780
find wooden spears that were preserved for almost 400,000

56:38.780 --> 56:42.940
years, according to some dating, which would have put them

56:42.940 --> 56:46.020
back in the time of erectus.

56:46.020 --> 56:52.420
So erectus, about 1.5 million years ago, they start making

56:52.420 --> 56:54.700
extremely complicated tools.

56:54.700 --> 56:56.700
They start traveling around the world.

56:56.700 --> 56:59.900
They start an evolutionary process physical where they

56:59.900 --> 57:03.820
start to get more articulate speech, the capacity for

57:03.820 --> 57:05.300
more articulate speech.

57:05.300 --> 57:07.540
They seem to be mastering boat travel.

57:07.540 --> 57:09.820
The ocean was never a barrier to erectus.

57:09.820 --> 57:12.180
Anytime there's an ocean barrier, you can expect to

57:12.180 --> 57:14.540
find erectus on the other side.

57:14.540 --> 57:17.740
They had organized settlements.

57:17.740 --> 57:22.340
So all of these tasks imply the likelihood of language.

57:22.340 --> 57:26.140
If we look at other species and we see species that are far

57:26.140 --> 57:28.780
removed from humans that seem to approximate some sort of

57:28.780 --> 57:33.260
linguistic ability, it's hardly surprising that what we

57:33.300 --> 57:35.540
would see an even greater ability in these creatures

57:35.540 --> 57:37.980
that were so much like us and had almost

57:37.980 --> 57:40.580
modern-sized brains.

57:40.580 --> 57:44.820
So if it's correct, there is evidence for language.

57:44.820 --> 57:48.060
Nobody could say this case has been proven, but it is

57:48.060 --> 57:48.820
highly likely.

57:48.820 --> 57:51.700
Once we take off the burden of languages looking like

57:51.700 --> 57:54.660
modern languages and we realize that a language is the

57:54.660 --> 57:57.620
transfer of information by the discovery and use of

57:57.620 --> 58:01.020
symbols and elaboration of those symbols over time, then

58:01.020 --> 58:03.860
we see a gradual evolution of language and we see

58:03.860 --> 58:07.420
evidence of erectus and no reason to withhold the

58:07.420 --> 58:10.340
judgment that they had language to account for all the

58:10.340 --> 58:14.020
different things that they were able to accomplish in

58:14.020 --> 58:16.020
their long history.

58:16.020 --> 58:17.620
They were preceded by these guys.

58:17.620 --> 58:22.820
These are just the various species of Australopithecines.

58:22.820 --> 58:27.060
Nature experimented a lot before it got to us.

58:27.060 --> 58:30.860
That could mean that we're the best or it could mean that

58:30.860 --> 58:34.820
it doesn't necessarily mean that we're the best.

58:34.820 --> 58:40.500
And when we ask where erectus went, just look around.

58:40.500 --> 58:43.020
We are erectus.

58:43.020 --> 58:52.140
Erectus was the ancestor of Neanderthal, of sapiens, of

58:52.140 --> 58:55.980
every other human creature that has existed.

58:55.980 --> 58:58.900
They were the smartest creatures the world had ever seen.

58:58.900 --> 59:00.340
They were the most widely traveled.

59:00.340 --> 59:03.220
They sailed, they built fire, they had settlements.

59:03.220 --> 59:08.060
They had strong evidence for symbolism in their tools.

59:08.060 --> 59:11.820
It's very difficult to see why we would withhold the

59:11.820 --> 59:16.460
judgment that they likely had language.

59:16.460 --> 59:20.020
And what they had to have had was more than simply grunts

59:20.020 --> 59:21.500
and squeals.

59:21.500 --> 59:24.300
They had to have something that was able to communicate

59:24.300 --> 59:27.700
actual content about the world around them, the kind of

59:27.700 --> 59:29.820
thing that would have been essential and been

59:29.820 --> 59:30.740
discovered and symboled.

59:30.740 --> 59:31.700
So thank you very much.

59:52.380 --> 59:53.940
We have time for a few questions.

59:53.940 --> 59:57.180
If anyone wants to raise their hand, I can run this.

01:00:02.460 --> 01:00:02.700
Hello.

01:00:02.700 --> 01:00:04.180
Thank you for a nice talk.

01:00:04.180 --> 01:00:09.980
To my knowledge, what is peculiar to Homo sapiens is

01:00:09.980 --> 01:00:15.020
the use of actual, what we would today call, artwork,

01:00:15.020 --> 01:00:18.100
such as was seen, of course, in the stone caves in France

01:00:18.100 --> 01:00:21.220
and perhaps in Africa earlier.

01:00:21.220 --> 01:00:23.660
Your talk is the first I've heard where you can say that

01:00:23.660 --> 01:00:28.820
Homo erectus was actually doing, I don't know if you call it

01:00:28.820 --> 01:00:29.660
art or not.

01:00:29.660 --> 01:00:32.060
Of course, today we still don't know what is art and what

01:00:32.060 --> 01:00:34.660
is not, but that's another matter.

01:00:34.660 --> 01:00:38.020
But that is one thing that seems to have been peculiar.

01:00:38.020 --> 01:00:42.020
Even that occurred relatively late in the lifetime of

01:00:42.020 --> 01:00:43.260
Homo sapiens.

01:00:43.260 --> 01:00:46.300
Also, I'd be interested to know if you think Homo erectus,

01:00:46.300 --> 01:00:49.980
not only had learned how to use fire, but had actually

01:00:49.980 --> 01:00:51.180
learned how to make it.

01:00:51.180 --> 01:00:52.220
So thank you.

01:00:52.220 --> 01:00:54.780
Yeah.

01:00:54.780 --> 01:00:57.100
On fire, the archaeological evidence seems to be that,

01:00:57.100 --> 01:00:57.980
yes, they could make it.

01:00:57.980 --> 01:00:59.140
They had controlled use of fire.

01:00:59.140 --> 01:01:01.260
We find it regularly in their settlements.

01:01:01.260 --> 01:01:05.540
As far as artwork, this is a red herring that a lot of

01:01:05.540 --> 01:01:10.340
archaeologists have thought to be somewhat important,

01:01:10.340 --> 01:01:12.540
because we think of art as symbolic.

01:01:12.540 --> 01:01:15.180
Actually, some art is symbolic, but a lot of art,

01:01:15.180 --> 01:01:17.980
especially representational art, is simply iconic.

01:01:17.980 --> 01:01:20.140
It's a lower level of cognitive

01:01:20.140 --> 01:01:21.340
development than symbolism.

01:01:21.340 --> 01:01:27.260
So art is a wonderful accomplishment, but it's not

01:01:27.260 --> 01:01:29.180
crucial to the linguistic line.

01:01:29.180 --> 01:01:31.900
It's a sort of red herring to think that if we find

01:01:31.900 --> 01:01:35.300
painting, it's almost certain that if we find painting,

01:01:35.300 --> 01:01:36.300
they could talk.

01:01:36.300 --> 01:01:39.860
But there's no argument from that to that if we don't find

01:01:39.860 --> 01:01:41.660
painting, they couldn't talk.

01:01:41.660 --> 01:01:43.460
Painting is just a development.

01:01:43.460 --> 01:01:45.460
Cultures develop over time.

01:01:45.460 --> 01:01:48.180
And I know of many cultures that I've done research on in

01:01:48.180 --> 01:01:50.500
the Amazon that have no art, but they certainly can talk.

01:01:54.980 --> 01:01:59.860
They don't do anything that is more elaborate in some ways

01:01:59.860 --> 01:02:01.420
than Homo erectus did.

01:02:01.420 --> 01:02:04.300
Homo erectus was a hunter-gatherer ban.

01:02:04.300 --> 01:02:08.820
And so we find many cultures today that live fairly

01:02:08.820 --> 01:02:10.140
similarly.

01:02:10.140 --> 01:02:11.180
They're a lot smarter.

01:02:11.180 --> 01:02:12.100
They have bigger brains.

01:02:12.100 --> 01:02:15.500
They can think of other things.

01:02:15.500 --> 01:02:17.940
And if you take them out of the hunter-gatherer ban and raise

01:02:17.940 --> 01:02:21.100
them in a city, they'll be unrecognizable for anybody else

01:02:21.100 --> 01:02:23.540
who was raised in the city, which I doubt would be the case

01:02:23.540 --> 01:02:24.380
for Homo erectus.

01:02:24.380 --> 01:02:31.220
But at the same time, art doesn't.

01:02:31.220 --> 01:02:33.580
We want to say that art represents language because

01:02:33.580 --> 01:02:35.780
it's complicated cultural accomplishment.

01:02:35.780 --> 01:02:40.620
And it can be symbolic, but it's often simply iconic.

01:02:40.620 --> 01:02:43.540
So art seems to be a separate cultural development that is

01:02:43.540 --> 01:02:45.420
off the line of language evolution.

01:02:45.420 --> 01:02:49.780
And I don't find it convincing to say that art is either here

01:02:49.780 --> 01:02:52.580
nor there when it comes to language evolution.

01:03:01.300 --> 01:03:04.180
Tasty.

01:03:04.180 --> 01:03:07.940
How would you describe the limitations of their language?

01:03:07.940 --> 01:03:08.780
Of erectus?

01:03:08.780 --> 01:03:09.620
Yes.

01:03:09.620 --> 01:03:16.820
So I work with languages that have similar properties.

01:03:16.820 --> 01:03:19.540
I mean, so in other words, if you think about what the

01:03:19.540 --> 01:03:23.660
simplest grammar could be, just words in a linear order, I've

01:03:23.660 --> 01:03:24.860
worked with languages like that.

01:03:24.860 --> 01:03:28.780
And the fact is they can say anything we can say.

01:03:28.780 --> 01:03:32.380
The complicated grammars that we have have very useful

01:03:32.380 --> 01:03:35.980
communicative functions, but they are not necessary to

01:03:35.980 --> 01:03:39.300
express modern thought or complicated thought.

01:03:39.300 --> 01:03:43.700
So the fact that somebody, we can say they have a simple

01:03:43.700 --> 01:03:46.020
grammar doesn't mean they have simple thought.

01:03:46.020 --> 01:03:49.140
That's another thing that has happened in the history of

01:03:49.140 --> 01:03:52.740
anthropology and linguistics to somehow think that language

01:03:52.740 --> 01:03:54.260
is the mirror of thought.

01:03:54.260 --> 01:03:55.740
And it doesn't have to be.

01:03:55.740 --> 01:03:57.300
There are a lot of things.

01:03:57.300 --> 01:04:00.620
For example, I work with hunter-gatherer groups that

01:04:00.620 --> 01:04:03.460
have very few words for time.

01:04:03.460 --> 01:04:05.420
Does this mean they don't know there was yesterday?

01:04:05.420 --> 01:04:07.940
So the Piedohan, for example, have no word for yesterday and

01:04:07.940 --> 01:04:09.020
no word for tomorrow.

01:04:09.020 --> 01:04:11.580
And we often find that this or that culture doesn't have a

01:04:11.580 --> 01:04:15.260
word for X, and so we drive all kinds of conclusions from it.

01:04:15.260 --> 01:04:17.500
But I don't see any conclusions to draw from that.

01:04:17.500 --> 01:04:18.940
They can think about those things.

01:04:18.940 --> 01:04:21.220
Everybody knows they got up yesterday, and they're getting

01:04:21.220 --> 01:04:23.220
up today, and they'll probably get up tomorrow.

01:04:23.220 --> 01:04:25.500
But the fact that they choose not to talk about them is a

01:04:25.500 --> 01:04:27.940
separate kind of cultural value.

01:04:27.940 --> 01:04:33.460
So I don't find the simplicity of grammar connected very

01:04:33.460 --> 01:04:35.420
tightly to the complexity of thought.

01:04:39.980 --> 01:04:47.780
Yeah, if they had symbols, they probably didn't have many

01:04:47.780 --> 01:04:48.980
limitations.

01:04:48.980 --> 01:04:51.660
I mean, you could say maybe they had the intelligence of an

01:04:51.660 --> 01:04:55.060
eight-year-old or a 10-year-old sapient's child.

01:04:55.060 --> 01:04:57.460
No way to really know that, but let's say they did.

01:04:57.460 --> 01:04:59.180
Eight-year-olds can talk a lot.

01:05:02.140 --> 01:05:08.500
I'm curious if we know how easy or difficult it is to know

01:05:08.500 --> 01:05:14.380
whether a tool that they used was made by them and not

01:05:14.380 --> 01:05:15.660
created by nature.

01:05:15.660 --> 01:05:18.340
How can we discern?

01:05:18.340 --> 01:05:20.780
Well, it's always very hard when you're going back in time to

01:05:20.780 --> 01:05:24.660
have dating methods that can link them to a species.

01:05:24.660 --> 01:05:28.180
So if you find a tool that's 600,000 years old, they were

01:05:28.180 --> 01:05:30.580
the only ones around.

01:05:30.580 --> 01:05:33.860
Nobody else was around, so they made it.

01:05:33.860 --> 01:05:37.940
But if you find a tool that was 150,000 years old, well,

01:05:37.940 --> 01:05:40.580
there were a lot of species of humans around at that time.

01:05:40.580 --> 01:05:43.580
So narrowing it down to Homo erectus becomes more

01:05:43.580 --> 01:05:47.820
difficult, but you can guess based on the settlement

01:05:47.820 --> 01:05:48.260
patterns.

01:05:48.260 --> 01:05:50.500
But it's difficult to tell with precision once you start

01:05:50.500 --> 01:05:54.300
getting into the area where other Homo species were

01:05:54.300 --> 01:05:55.780
existing side by side.

01:05:59.620 --> 01:06:01.380
Oh, that it was made.

01:06:01.380 --> 01:06:06.060
Some of the older on tools could have just one rock fell on

01:06:06.060 --> 01:06:07.300
another, and suddenly you get this.

01:06:07.300 --> 01:06:10.340
But these Atulian tools, these more complex tools, there's

01:06:10.340 --> 01:06:12.300
no way they came about by accident.

01:06:12.300 --> 01:06:16.540
They had to have been designed, planned, and constructed

01:06:16.540 --> 01:06:18.420
with a great deal of craftsmanship.

01:06:18.420 --> 01:06:22.700
It takes hundreds of hours, at least 500 hours, from what I've

01:06:22.700 --> 01:06:25.860
heard, for graduate student in archaeology to be able to make

01:06:25.860 --> 01:06:30.820
an Atulian handaxe, not to make, that's how long it takes

01:06:30.820 --> 01:06:31.340
to learn it.

01:06:31.340 --> 01:06:32.980
They can make them faster after that.

01:06:38.300 --> 01:06:44.180
I'm curious to know what led to the, I guess, eventual demise

01:06:44.180 --> 01:06:48.580
of this species given your talk, how successful they have

01:06:48.580 --> 01:06:52.380
been at traveling and establishing communities

01:06:52.380 --> 01:06:54.380
all around the world.

01:06:54.380 --> 01:06:58.820
So I'm just curious, what led to a global end

01:06:58.820 --> 01:07:01.380
to such a successful run?

01:07:01.380 --> 01:07:05.020
Yeah, that's a very good question.

01:07:05.020 --> 01:07:07.060
We're the only ones left standing.

01:07:07.100 --> 01:07:09.980
So did they die out?

01:07:09.980 --> 01:07:11.260
Did they become us?

01:07:11.260 --> 01:07:13.380
One answer is they didn't die.

01:07:13.380 --> 01:07:15.580
We are them.

01:07:15.580 --> 01:07:19.740
The other answer is that Homo sapiens is, they're smarter,

01:07:19.740 --> 01:07:22.940
and one thing we've shown as a species throughout our history

01:07:22.940 --> 01:07:27.420
is the ability to slaughter other people that look like us.

01:07:27.420 --> 01:07:30.540
So the fact that the Homo sapiens might have killed them all

01:07:30.540 --> 01:07:33.700
doesn't seem to have, that doesn't seem to be totally

01:07:33.700 --> 01:07:35.620
outside the realm of possibility either.

01:07:35.620 --> 01:07:38.580
So I don't know why they disappeared.

01:07:38.580 --> 01:07:40.780
And I was asked a similar question

01:07:40.780 --> 01:07:42.180
when I was giving a talk in Hungary,

01:07:42.180 --> 01:07:44.140
and I probably should have been more careful.

01:07:44.140 --> 01:07:47.260
But I said, the Hungarian Jews didn't disappear

01:07:47.260 --> 01:07:50.780
because they didn't have language.

01:07:50.780 --> 01:07:54.060
So there are all kinds of reasons that people disappear.

01:07:55.060 --> 01:08:06.060
Hi.

01:08:06.060 --> 01:08:07.700
You briefly said at the beginning

01:08:07.700 --> 01:08:10.020
that the Homo erectus, there was one

01:08:10.020 --> 01:08:12.060
that they found a hyoid bone in it,

01:08:12.060 --> 01:08:15.540
so that you're speculating that then they have vocal cords

01:08:15.540 --> 01:08:20.780
and they could then produce sounds.

01:08:21.020 --> 01:08:25.420
So are you thinking the later species all had the hyoid bones

01:08:25.420 --> 01:08:27.540
and could vocalize?

01:08:27.540 --> 01:08:29.580
We don't really know.

01:08:29.580 --> 01:08:32.540
Some people, to come to Fitch would believe

01:08:32.540 --> 01:08:36.460
that we almost certainly had, Homo erectus

01:08:36.460 --> 01:08:38.980
had this modern speech capability.

01:08:38.980 --> 01:08:42.860
My point is that it really doesn't matter.

01:08:42.860 --> 01:08:45.500
Evolving modern speech is a tremendous advantage,

01:08:45.500 --> 01:08:47.660
but it's not a necessary condition,

01:08:47.660 --> 01:08:50.180
nor is it a sufficient condition for having language.

01:08:50.180 --> 01:08:52.900
We can look at other species that seem to have.

01:08:52.900 --> 01:08:56.140
We listen to a parrot.

01:08:56.140 --> 01:08:58.380
They can produce human speech sounds fairly well.

01:08:58.380 --> 01:09:00.660
That's so it shows that it's not a sufficient condition

01:09:00.660 --> 01:09:04.100
for language, and the fact that erectus might not have had it

01:09:04.100 --> 01:09:05.980
would show that it's not a necessary condition

01:09:05.980 --> 01:09:08.980
for language, because we have deaf people today

01:09:08.980 --> 01:09:10.580
who talk with American sign language

01:09:10.580 --> 01:09:12.500
and say anything we can say.

01:09:12.500 --> 01:09:15.980
So language is looking for a physical medium

01:09:15.980 --> 01:09:20.100
to be transmitted, and that usually, and most efficiently,

01:09:20.100 --> 01:09:21.140
is human speech.

01:09:21.140 --> 01:09:23.300
And with quantal vowels and modern speech,

01:09:23.300 --> 01:09:25.500
we can communicate much more clearly,

01:09:25.500 --> 01:09:28.500
but it's neither necessary nor sufficient to have language.

01:09:33.500 --> 01:09:35.020
They could have produced sounds.

01:09:35.020 --> 01:09:36.380
They might not have been very clear,

01:09:36.380 --> 01:09:38.700
but the reason that chimpanzees don't talk

01:09:38.700 --> 01:09:41.020
is not because they can't produce sounds.

01:09:41.020 --> 01:09:42.180
They produce enough sounds.

01:09:42.180 --> 01:09:45.540
My point about computers is that any creature that

01:09:45.540 --> 01:09:49.820
can produce two sounds could talk in principle.

01:09:49.860 --> 01:09:55.100
My dog makes a lot of sounds, and I understand a lot of them.

01:09:55.100 --> 01:09:57.060
I'm trying to figure out if any of them are symbols,

01:09:57.060 --> 01:10:03.100
but they're certainly, she's very articulate in letting

01:10:03.100 --> 01:10:06.260
me know when it's time to do certain things.

01:10:06.260 --> 01:10:11.500
So I have mastered a repertoire of her sounds,

01:10:11.500 --> 01:10:12.500
and she uses them.

01:10:12.500 --> 01:10:14.340
But that doesn't mean that she, I

01:10:14.340 --> 01:10:17.820
don't expect her to give me advice about how

01:10:17.820 --> 01:10:22.260
to find my grandmother in Ancestry.com or something

01:10:22.260 --> 01:10:23.340
like that.

01:10:23.340 --> 01:10:24.780
These are cultural accomplishments

01:10:24.780 --> 01:10:30.060
that require a much greater set of symbols.

01:10:30.060 --> 01:10:32.620
I think that is about all we have time for.

01:10:32.620 --> 01:10:34.340
Give another hand to Daniel Everett.

01:10:34.340 --> 01:10:35.140
Thanks, everybody.

01:10:35.140 --> 01:10:36.140
Thank you.

